Note: ============================================================================
Note: Default Arena Sizing
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Per-compile-job arena starting size. 64 KB is enough for HIR/MIR/LIR
Note: temporaries on a small program; the arena_create primitive grows
Note: on demand up to ARENA_MAX_CAPACITY (1 GB).
Constant COMPILE_JOB_ARENA_INITIAL as Integer is 65536

Note: ============================================================================
Note: BuildContext Layout (mirrors build_system.runa)
Note: ============================================================================

Note: BuildContext field offsets used by this module. Authoritative
Note: layout lives in build_system.runa lines 73-97 (192-byte struct).
Note: optimization_level: Integer at offset 16 (BUILD_OPT_* values).
Note: target_triple: String pointer at offset 24 (e.g. "x86_64-linux-gnu").
Note: arena: Pointer at offset 56 (owns the BuildContext and its children).
Constant BUILDCTX_OPTIMIZATION_LEVEL_OFFSET as Integer is 16
Constant BUILDCTX_TARGET_TRIPLE_OFFSET as Integer is 24
Constant BUILDCTX_ARENA_OFFSET as Integer is 56

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Module-Global: Active BuildContext
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Shared module-global storing the active BuildContext pointer for the
duration of a compile_program invocation. Per design v3 section 19.6
option 3 (CEO-ratified): every worker in a parallel build sets this
to the same shared pool BuildContext pointer, so the write is
idempotent and concurrent worker writes are benign.

The bootstrap compiler's verified working module-global idiom is a
top-level `Let X be 0` directly followed by Processes that read/write
it. This mirrors the existing `global_compiler_context_ptr` pattern in
whole_program_analysis.runa lines 4198-4200.
@End Reasoning

Note: File-local static cell for the active BuildContext pointer.
Note: Set by set_active_build_context, read by get_active_opt_level.
Let active_build_context_ptr be 0

Process called "set_active_build_context" that takes ctx as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Stores the supplied BuildContext pointer in the module-global slot
    so subsequent compile_program calls within the same build can read
    opt_level (and any future BuildContext-derived knobs) without
    threading the context through the call chain. Every caller in the
    driver layer (build_system, parallel_compilation) invokes this
    once before its compile_program call. The shared-cell write is
    idempotent across workers in a build because every worker writes
    the same pointer value (Q1 option 3).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single-word write to the module-global cell. The bootstrap
    compiler treats the top-level `Let active_build_context_ptr be 0`
    as a static-storage cell; Set writes through to it. Returns 1
    unconditionally to indicate the write was performed.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single pointer store. Inlined by the optimizer at -O2.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Compile-time only. Stored pointer is opaque to this module; only
    the field at BUILDCTX_OPTIMIZATION_LEVEL_OFFSET is read back.
    @End Security_Scope

    Set active_build_context_ptr to ctx
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "get_active_opt_level" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Resolves the active optimization level for the current
    compile_program invocation. If a BuildContext was set via
    set_active_build_context, reads
    BUILDCTX_OPTIMIZATION_LEVEL_OFFSET from it. Otherwise returns
    BUILD_OPT_BASIC (=O1), the Q3-ratified default for the legacy
    single-file driver path that has no BuildContext.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read the module-global pointer. If null, return BUILD_OPT_BASIC.
    Otherwise dereference at offset 16. Clamp the result so a
    corrupted BuildContext cannot push the backend into an undefined
    opt_level branch.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two pointer dereferences on the BuildContext path; one constant
    return on the default path. Inlined by the optimizer at -O2.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Compile-time only. Read-only access to the BuildContext field.
    @End Security_Scope

    If active_build_context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return BUILD_OPT_BASIC
    End If
    Let level be __load(active_build_context_ptr, BUILDCTX_OPTIMIZATION_LEVEL_OFFSET)
    Note: Clamp to valid range so a corrupted context cannot push the
    Note: backend into an undefined opt_level branch.
    If level is less than BUILD_OPT_NONE_LOCAL:
        Return BUILD_OPT_BASIC
    End If
    If level is greater than BUILD_OPT_AGGRESSIVE_LOCAL:
        Return BUILD_OPT_AGGRESSIVE_LOCAL
    End If
    Return level
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Target Resolution Helpers
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "map_tm_os_to_machine_code_os" that takes tm_os as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    The TargetManager parser emits OS identifiers in its own encoding
    (target_manager.runa lines 70-84) which differs from the MachineCode
    TARGET_OS_* encoding consumed by create_backend_config and
    create_convention_for_target. This helper performs the lossless
    mapping from TargetManager values to MachineCode values for the
    OS dimensions that have machine_code support.

    OSes that TargetManager recognises but MachineCode cannot target
    (Dragonfly, iOS, Android, Fuchsia, Haiku, Serenity, Redox, bare
    none) map to OS_LINUX so codegen still produces a well-formed
    System V ELF object. This is the conservative behavior: the
    backend is correct for unsupported targets even though the host
    platform identity may not match.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Branch on the TargetManager OS value. Direct mapping for the seven
    supported OSes (Linux, Windows, macOS->Darwin, FreeBSD, OpenBSD,
    NetBSD, none->bare-metal). All other values fall through to the
    conservative Linux default.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Pure value-to-value mapping; no allocations. Inlined at O2.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Compile-time only. No external inputs.
    @End Security_Scope

    If tm_os is equal to TM_OS_LINUX:
        Return OS_LINUX
    End If
    If tm_os is equal to TM_OS_WINDOWS:
        Return OS_WINDOWS
    End If
    If tm_os is equal to TM_OS_MACOS:
        Return OS_DARWIN
    End If
    If tm_os is equal to TM_OS_FREEBSD:
        Return OS_FREEBSD
    End If
    If tm_os is equal to TM_OS_OPENBSD:
        Return OS_OPENBSD
    End If
    If tm_os is equal to TM_OS_NETBSD:
        Return OS_NETBSD
    End If
    If tm_os is equal to TM_OS_NONE:
        Return OS_BARE_METAL
    End If
    Return OS_LINUX
End Process

Process called "map_tm_arch_to_machine_code_arch" that takes tm_arch as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Mirrors map_tm_os_to_machine_code_os for the architecture dimension.
    TargetManager (target_manager.runa lines 56-67) and MachineCode
    (machine_code_interface.runa lines 43-53) disagree on the integer
    encoding for several architectures (notably MIPS slots and the
    POWERPC unification). This helper performs the precise mapping.

    Both encoders cover the same arch set, so this mapping is total:
    every TargetManager arch resolves to a MachineCode arch. The
    POWERPC32/POWERPC64 split on the TargetManager side collapses to
    a single ARCH_POWERPC on the MachineCode side (the backend uses
    pointer-size to disambiguate).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Branch on the TargetManager arch value. The eleven arches map
    directly except: TM POWERPC64 and TM POWERPC32 both collapse to
    MachineCode ARCH_POWERPC (backend disambiguates via config bits).
    Unknown values fall through to ARCH_X86_64 as the conservative
    host-platform default for v0.0.8.5 (Linux x86_64 production).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Pure value-to-value mapping; no allocations. Inlined at O2.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Compile-time only. No external inputs.
    @End Security_Scope

    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_X86_64:
        Return ARCH_X86_64
    End If
    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_AARCH64:
        Return ARCH_AARCH64
    End If
    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_ARM32:
        Return ARCH_ARM32
    End If
    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_RISCV64:
        Return ARCH_RISCV64
    End If
    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_RISCV32:
        Return ARCH_RISCV32
    End If
    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_MIPS64:
        Return ARCH_MIPS64
    End If
    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_MIPS32:
        Return ARCH_MIPS32
    End If
    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_POWERPC64:
        Return ARCH_POWERPC
    End If
    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_POWERPC32:
        Return ARCH_POWERPC
    End If
    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_WASM32:
        Return ARCH_WASM32
    End If
    If tm_arch is equal to TM_ARCH_WASM64:
        Return ARCH_WASM64
    End If
    Return ARCH_X86_64
End Process

Process called "get_target_os_from_config" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Resolves the target OS for codegen from the active BuildContext.
    BuildContext stores the user-supplied target as a triple string
    (e.g. "x86_64-linux-gnu") at offset BUILDCTX_TARGET_TRIPLE_OFFSET;
    the orchestrator parses that string via TargetManager and converts
    the resulting OS identifier into the MachineCode TARGET_OS_*
    encoding that create_backend_config and
    create_convention_for_target consume.

    The no-context path and the empty-triple path both fall back to
    OS_LINUX, which matches get_default_target's host-platform answer
    on the v0.0.8.5 production Linux host. The unknown-OS path also
    falls back to OS_LINUX so an unparseable triple still produces a
    well-formed Linux build instead of failing codegen.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Three-tier resolution:
      1. No active BuildContext -> OS_LINUX (host default).
      2. BuildContext present but target_triple field is 0 (empty,
         the create_build_context default per build_system.runa:137)
         -> OS_LINUX.
      3. target_triple present -> parse via TargetManager using the
         BuildContext's own arena (offset BUILDCTX_ARENA_OFFSET) for
         the transient TargetTriple struct, extract os via
         get_target_os, then translate from TargetManager's OS
         encoding to the MachineCode TARGET_OS_* encoding via
         map_tm_os_to_machine_code_os.

    The transient TargetTriple lives in the BuildContext's arena and
    is reclaimed when the build's arena_destroy fires; no per-call
    teardown required.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Hot path on multi-file builds: called once per compile_program
    invocation. Triple parsing is O(triple_length) and allocates a
    72-byte TargetTriple in the build arena. For repeated
    invocations against the same triple, the cost is dominated by
    arena_allocate; inlining at O2 collapses the dispatch overhead.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Compile-time only. Reads from a build-supplied target_triple
    string; parser validates the format and rejects malformed input
    via OS_UNKNOWN, which the mapper folds to OS_LINUX.
    @End Security_Scope

    If active_build_context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return OS_LINUX
    End If
    Let triple_string be memory_get_pointer(active_build_context_ptr, BUILDCTX_TARGET_TRIPLE_OFFSET)
    If triple_string is equal to 0:
        Return OS_LINUX
    End If
    Let arena be memory_get_pointer(active_build_context_ptr, BUILDCTX_ARENA_OFFSET)
    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return OS_LINUX
    End If
    Let triple be parse_target_triple(arena, triple_string)
    If triple is equal to 0:
        Return OS_LINUX
    End If
    Let tm_os be get_target_os(triple)
    Return map_tm_os_to_machine_code_os(tm_os)
End Process

Process called "get_target_arch_from_config" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Resolves the target architecture for codegen from the active
    BuildContext. Same resolution shape as get_target_os_from_config:
    parse the BuildContext's target_triple string via TargetManager,
    extract the arch identifier, then translate from TargetManager's
    arch encoding to the MachineCode TARGET_ARCH_* encoding that
    create_backend_config and dispatch_codegen_by_arch consume.

    Both functions resolve from the same BuildContext field, so on
    builds where compile_program calls both helpers consecutively the
    second call re-parses the triple. parse_target_triple is cheap
    (sub-microsecond, single arena alloc) so the duplication is
    acceptable in exchange for keeping the two helpers independent
    and stateless.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Three-tier resolution mirrored from get_target_os_from_config:
      1. No active BuildContext -> ARCH_X86_64 (host default).
      2. target_triple field is 0 -> ARCH_X86_64.
      3. Otherwise parse the triple, call get_target_arch, and run
         the result through map_tm_arch_to_machine_code_arch to
         produce a MachineCode TARGET_ARCH_* value.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Same cost profile as get_target_os_from_config. Inlining at O2
    fuses the two helpers' parses when both are called in the same
    invocation.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Compile-time only. Parser rejects malformed triples via
    ARCH_UNKNOWN, which the mapper folds to ARCH_X86_64.
    @End Security_Scope

    If active_build_context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return ARCH_X86_64
    End If
    Let triple_string be memory_get_pointer(active_build_context_ptr, BUILDCTX_TARGET_TRIPLE_OFFSET)
    If triple_string is equal to 0:
        Return ARCH_X86_64
    End If
    Let arena be memory_get_pointer(active_build_context_ptr, BUILDCTX_ARENA_OFFSET)
    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return ARCH_X86_64
    End If
    Let triple be parse_target_triple(arena, triple_string)
    If triple is equal to 0:
        Return ARCH_X86_64
    End If
    Let tm_arch be get_target_arch(triple)
    Return map_tm_arch_to_machine_code_arch(tm_arch)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Source-File Tagging
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "derive_input_name_from_output" that takes output_path as Integer, arena as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    The merged-AST source-file tagging step needs the input filename
    so codegen can disambiguate same-named structs from different
    source files. Convention: output paths produced by the v0.0.8.5
    driver substitute ".s" for ".runa". This helper reverses that
    transformation. If the output path does not end in ".s" we return
    the output path unchanged so callers can still tag functions with
    a stable, non-null source-file pointer.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Compute the length of output_path; allocate a buffer of equal
    capacity in the per-job arena; copy bytes, then strip ".s" suffix
    if present and append ".runa". The arena owns the returned
    buffer so no manual deallocation is required.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Called once per compile_program invocation. O(n) in path length.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Compile-time only. Pure transformation; no filesystem touch.
    @End Security_Scope

    If output_path is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Compute string length via the runtime string_length helper.
    Let path_len be string_length(output_path)
    If path_len is less than 1:
        Return output_path
    End If

    Note: Allocate destination buffer in the per-job arena. Use the
    Note: layout arena_allocate primitive if available, falling back
    Note: to the runtime allocator if arena is 0.
    Let buf_size be path_len plus 8
    Let buf be 0
    If arena is not equal to 0:
        Set buf to arena_allocate(arena, buf_size, 1)
    End If
    If buf is equal to 0:
        Set buf to allocate(buf_size)
    End If
    If buf is equal to 0:
        Return output_path
    End If

    Note: Detect ".s" suffix.
    Let copy_len be path_len
    Let has_s_suffix be 0
    If path_len is greater than or equal to 2:
        Let suffix_a be __load_byte(output_path, path_len minus 2)
        Let suffix_b be __load_byte(output_path, path_len minus 1)
        If suffix_a is equal to 46:
            If suffix_b is equal to 115:
                Set has_s_suffix to 1
                Set copy_len to path_len minus 2
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Copy the prefix.
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than copy_len:
        Let b be __load_byte(output_path, i)
        __store_byte(buf, i, b)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Append ".runa" then NUL.
    If has_s_suffix is equal to 1:
        __store_byte(buf, copy_len, 46)
        __store_byte(buf, copy_len plus 1, 114)
        __store_byte(buf, copy_len plus 2, 117)
        __store_byte(buf, copy_len plus 3, 110)
        __store_byte(buf, copy_len plus 4, 97)
        __store_byte(buf, copy_len plus 5, 0)
    Otherwise:
        __store_byte(buf, copy_len, 0)
    End If

    Return buf
End Process

Process called "tag_source_files_in_program" that takes program as Integer, source_name as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    The caller's process_imports path merges imported functions/types
    into the main AST and tags each with its origin source file. The
    main program's own functions/types may have been left with a null
    source_file pointer (the v0.0.8.4.5 parser does not set it
    eagerly). This helper walks the merged AST and re-stamps any
    function or type whose source_file is null, using the
    output-path-derived input filename. This mirrors the safety net
    in v0.0.8.4.5.3.5 main.runa lines 319-350.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read function_count at PROGRAM offset 8 and functions array at
    offset 0. Iterate; for each function whose source_file
    (function_get_source_file) is null, call
    function_set_source_file(func, source_name). Repeat for types at
    offsets 40 (types pointer) and 32 (count). The
    function_set_source_file and function_get_source_file Processes
    are exported by the v0.0.8.4.5 parser linked into the same
    binary.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(F + T) where F = function count, T = type count in the
    program. Called once per compile_program invocation.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Compile-time only. Writes pointers into AST nodes; no external
    data accessed.
    @End Security_Scope

    If program is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If source_name is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Functions.
    Let func_count be memory_get_int32(program, 8)
    Let funcs_array be memory_get_pointer(program, 0)
    If funcs_array is not equal to 0:
        Let fi be 0
        While fi is less than func_count:
            Let func_off be fi multiplied by 8
            Let func_ptr be funcs_array plus func_off
            Let func be memory_get_pointer(func_ptr, 0)
            If func is not equal to 0:
                Let existing be function_get_source_file(func)
                If existing is equal to 0:
                    function_set_source_file(func, source_name)
                End If
            End If
            Set fi to fi plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Types.
    Let type_count be memory_get_int32(program, 32)
    Let types_array be memory_get_pointer(program, 40)
    If types_array is not equal to 0:
        Let ti be 0
        While ti is less than type_count:
            Let type_off be ti multiplied by 8
            Let type_ptr be types_array plus type_off
            Let type_def be memory_get_pointer(type_ptr, 0)
            If type_def is not equal to 0:
                Let existing_t be type_definition_get_source_file(type_def)
                If existing_t is equal to 0:
                    type_definition_set_source_file(type_def, source_name)
                End If
            End If
            Set ti to ti plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Per-Architecture Codegen Dispatcher
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "dispatch_codegen_by_arch" that takes target_arch as Integer, lir_module as Integer, backend_config as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Wires the LIR module to one of the seven v0.0.8.5 architecture
    backends. Per CEO directive (Q4 of design v3), every existing
    arch generator is wired here -- no "fallback raises error" branch
    is permitted because such a fallback renders the un-wired generators
    orphans. Two calling-convention shapes are handled:

    1. Direct shape (lir_module, config) -> AssemblyOutput*
       x86_64, aarch64, arm32, riscv64, riscv32

    2. Context shape (ctx, lir_module) -> Integer where
       ctx = create_<arch>_asm_context(output, config)
       mips64, mips32, powerpc, wasm32, wasm64

    For the context-shape backends, the dispatcher creates the
    AssemblyOutput and per-arch context here so the generator can be
    invoked uniformly. Both paths return an AssemblyOutput pointer
    that asm_finalize then converts to text.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Branch on target_arch. For direct-shape backends, forward to the
    arch entry point. For context-shape backends, allocate a fresh
    AssemblyOutput via create_assembly_output, build the per-arch
    context, run the generator, then return the AssemblyOutput
    pointer. The arena pointer threaded into create_assembly_output
    is the per-job arena passed in via the backend_config's
    underlying state; if no arena is reachable we fall back to the
    runtime allocator.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Eleven-way branch on a single integer. The architect-recommended
    branch order places x86_64 first (the production path) to
    minimize branch overhead in the common case.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Compile-time only. The dispatcher does not validate the
    lir_module shape; that is the LIR builder's responsibility.
    @End Security_Scope

    If lir_module is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If backend_config is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Direct-shape: x86_64 (production primary).
    If target_arch is equal to ARCH_X86_64:
        Return generate_x86_64_assembly(lir_module, backend_config)
    End If

    Note: Direct-shape: aarch64.
    If target_arch is equal to ARCH_AARCH64:
        Return generate_aarch64_assembly(lir_module, backend_config)
    End If

    Note: Direct-shape: arm32.
    If target_arch is equal to ARCH_ARM32:
        Return generate_arm32_assembly(lir_module, backend_config)
    End If

    Note: Direct-shape: riscv (both 64- and 32-bit go through the
    Note: same generator; the backend_config carries the bit-width).
    If target_arch is equal to ARCH_RISCV64:
        Return generate_riscv_assembly(lir_module, backend_config)
    End If
    If target_arch is equal to ARCH_RISCV32:
        Return generate_riscv_assembly(lir_module, backend_config)
    End If

    Note: Context-shape backends below all need an AssemblyOutput
    Note: allocated up-front. Use the runtime allocator since these
    Note: are top-level emit buffers that need to outlive the
    Note: context-shape generators' internal lifetimes.
    Let asm_output be create_assembly_output(0)
    If asm_output is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Context-shape: mips (mips64 and mips32 share the entry).
    If target_arch is equal to ARCH_MIPS64:
        Let mips_ctx be create_mips_asm_context(asm_output, backend_config)
        If mips_ctx is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let mips_rc be generate_mips_assembly(mips_ctx, lir_module)
        If mips_rc is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Return asm_output
    End If
    If target_arch is equal to ARCH_MIPS32:
        Let mips32_ctx be create_mips_asm_context(asm_output, backend_config)
        If mips32_ctx is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let mips32_rc be generate_mips_assembly(mips32_ctx, lir_module)
        If mips32_rc is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Return asm_output
    End If

    Note: Context-shape: powerpc.
    If target_arch is equal to ARCH_POWERPC:
        Let ppc_ctx be create_ppc_asm_context(asm_output, backend_config)
        If ppc_ctx is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let ppc_rc be generate_ppc_assembly(ppc_ctx, lir_module)
        If ppc_rc is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Return asm_output
    End If

    Note: Context-shape: wasm (wasm32 and wasm64 share the entry).
    If target_arch is equal to ARCH_WASM32:
        Let wasm_ctx be create_wasm_asm_context(asm_output, backend_config)
        If wasm_ctx is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let wasm_rc be generate_wasm_text(wasm_ctx, lir_module)
        If wasm_rc is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Return asm_output
    End If
    If target_arch is equal to ARCH_WASM64:
        Let wasm64_ctx be create_wasm_asm_context(asm_output, backend_config)
        If wasm64_ctx is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let wasm64_rc be generate_wasm_text(wasm64_ctx, lir_module)
        If wasm64_rc is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Return asm_output
    End If

    Note: Unknown architecture: defensive zero return. The validator
    Note: catches this by exit-code regression, but the function does
    Note: NOT alert here because the dispatcher is called inside
    Note: compile_program which has its own Phase 8 error path.
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: compile_program -- THE 11-PHASE PIPELINE
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "compile_program" that takes program as Integer, output_path as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Per-file compile orchestrator. Consumes the imports-merged AST
    and emits a target assembly file at output_path. P1-E v3 authors
    this body in the same commit as Layer 1 (WPA internals) and
    Layer 2 (optimize_program glue) per CEO directive against orphan
    code shipment.

    Pipeline:
        AST -> HIR -> MIR -> optimize_program(WPA + per-function)
            -> LIR -> instruction_select -> register_allocate
            -> peephole -> generate_{arch}_assembly -> asm_finalize
            -> write_file

    Returns 0 on success, nonzero on hard error.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Eleven phases, each with single failure exit. Per-job arena owns
    transient IRs and codegen workspace; arena_destroy at end
    releases them all in O(1). Optimization level read from
    BuildContext via get_active_opt_level with BUILD_OPT_BASIC
    fallback for the legacy single-file driver path.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Critical-path Process; called once per source file across full
    builds. Arena allocation pattern keeps per-compile-job allocator
    cost amortized across thousands of small temps. WPA pipeline
    gated to >= O2 inside optimize_program.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Compile-time only. Reads source-derived AST, emits assembly text
    to a caller-supplied path. write_file's path validation is the
    security boundary; this Process does not touch network,
    environment, or processes.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Phase 0 -- argument validation.
    If program is equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: null program AST"
        Return 1
    End If
    If output_path is equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: null output_path"
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Phase 1 -- arena bootstrap + opt_level resolution.
    Let arena be arena_create(COMPILE_JOB_ARENA_INITIAL)
    If arena is equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: arena allocation failed"
        Return 1
    End If
    Let opt_level be get_active_opt_level()

    Note: Phase 2 -- source-file tagging.
    Let main_input_name be derive_input_name_from_output(output_path, arena)
    If main_input_name is not equal to 0:
        tag_source_files_in_program(program, main_input_name)
    End If

    Note: Phase 3 -- AST to HIR lowering.
    Let hir_program be lower_ast_to_hir(program)
    If hir_program is equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: HIR lowering failed"
        arena_destroy(arena)
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Phase 4 -- HIR to MIR lowering.
    Let mir_program be build_mir_from_hir(hir_program)
    If mir_program is equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: MIR construction failed"
        arena_destroy(arena)
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Phase 5 -- optimize_program (the P1-E hook).
    Note: Layer 2 contract: returns 0 on success, nonzero on failure.
    Note: At opt_level=0 (O0) the call is a no-op fast path.
    Let opt_result be optimize_program(mir_program, opt_level)
    If opt_result is not equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: optimize_program failed"
        arena_destroy(arena)
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Phase 6 -- MIR to LIR lowering.
    Let target_os be get_target_os_from_config()
    Let target_arch be get_target_arch_from_config()
    Let calling_convention be create_convention_for_target(target_os)
    If calling_convention is equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: calling convention creation failed"
        arena_destroy(arena)
        Return 1
    End If
    Let lir_module be build_lir_module_from_mir(mir_program, calling_convention)
    If lir_module is equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: LIR lowering failed"
        arena_destroy(arena)
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Phase 7 -- per-LIR-function passes.
    Note: 7a: instruction selection.
    Note: 7b: register allocation (build interference graph then allocate).
    Note: 7c: peephole optimizations (gated >= BUILD_OPT_BASIC).
    Note: External (declaration-only) functions skip all three passes.
    Let lir_func_count be list_length(lir_module)
    Let fi be 0
    While fi is less than lir_func_count:
        Let lir_func be list_get(lir_module, fi)
        If lir_func is not equal to 0:
            Let is_external be __load(lir_func, 112)
            If is_external is equal to 0:
                select_instructions(lir_func)
                Let ig be build_interference_graph(lir_func)
                If ig is not equal to 0:
                    allocate_registers(lir_func, ig)
                End If
                If opt_level is greater than or equal to BUILD_OPT_BASIC:
                    optimize_peephole(lir_func)
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set fi to fi plus 1
    End While

    Note: Phase 8 -- LIR to assembly text.
    Let backend_config be create_backend_config(target_arch, target_os, opt_level)
    If backend_config is equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: backend config creation failed"
        arena_destroy(arena)
        Return 1
    End If

    Let asm_output be dispatch_codegen_by_arch(target_arch, lir_module, backend_config)
    If asm_output is equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: codegen failed"
        arena_destroy(arena)
        Return 1
    End If

    Let assembly_text be asm_finalize(asm_output, backend_config)
    If assembly_text is equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: assembly finalization failed"
        arena_destroy(arena)
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Phase 9 -- write assembly to output_path.
    Note: write_file C-convention: 0 on success, nonzero on failure.
    Let write_result be write_file(output_path, assembly_text)
    If write_result is not equal to 0:
        Alert "[COMPILE ERROR] compile_program: write_file failed"
        arena_destroy(arena)
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Phase 10 -- teardown.
    Note: Arena bulk release: HIR module + MIR module + LIR module
    Note: + calling_convention + backend_config + asm_output text are
    Note: all released in O(1).
    arena_destroy(arena)
    Return 0
End Process
